# Critical extraction note: amidst uses **args4j
# single-dash-default-flag CLI pattern** at
# CommandLineParameters.java throughout — all
# flag names use SINGLE-DASH: `-mcpath`,
# `-mcjar`, `-biome-profiles`, `-world-type`,
# `-help`, `-version`.  args4j defaults to
# single-dash names — a UNIX traditional
# convention.  Distinct from R322 JCommander
# (`--long` double-dash default, `-X` short-
# dash), R276 picocli (`--long` default).
# args4j's single-dash default is a HISTORICAL
# UNIX style — corpus's **first documented
# single-dash-default-flag CLI pattern**.  args4j
# CAN use `--long` if explicitly specified in
# `name = "--long"`, but the convention is
# single-dash even for multi-character flag
# names.
#
# Critical extraction note: amidst uses **args4j
# `depends` and `forbids` declarative arrays**
# at CommandLineParameters.java:35-42, 44-51,
# 54-60, 87-93 — `@Option(name = "-mcjar", ...,
# depends = { "-mcjson" }, forbids = { "-profile"
# })` declares that `-mcjar` REQUIRES `-mcjson`
# also be given, and FORBIDS `-profile` from
# being given simultaneously.  Distinct from
# R322 JCommander (no built-in depends/forbids —
# requires custom IParameterValidator), R276
# picocli (`scope = ` and `defaultValue =` but
# no native depends/forbids), R315 Eiffel Gobo
# `AP_ALTERNATIVE_OPTIONS_LIST` (mutex via
# first-class object structure).  args4j's
# approach: DECLARATIVE `depends`/`forbids`
# STRING ARRAYS in the annotation — corpus's
# **first documented declarative-depends-and-
# forbids CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: amidst uses **args4j
# `OptionHandler<T>` SPI for custom type
# converters** at CommandLineParameters.java:
# 82-90 + 124-160 — `@Option(handler =
# SeedHandler.class)` references a static
# nested class `SeedHandler extends
# OptionHandler<WorldSeed>` that converts the
# argv string to a `WorldSeed` domain object.
# Distinct from R322 JCommander `converter =
# X.class` (uses `IStringConverter<T>`
# interface — SINGLE-arg conversion only),
# R276 picocli `@Option converter = X.class`
# (uses `ITypeConverter<T>`).  args4j's
# `OptionHandler<T>` is MORE POWERFUL because
# `parseArguments(Parameters params)` can
# CONSUME MULTIPLE TOKENS (returning the count)
# — useful for options like `-foo a b c d`
# that take a sub-list.  Corpus's **first
# documented multi-token-consuming-handler CLI
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: amidst uses **args4j
# `ParserProperties.defaults().with...()`
# builder for parser config** at Amidst.java:
# 56-60 — `new CmdLineParser(parameters,
# ParserProperties.defaults().withShowDefaults
# (false).withUsageWidth(120).withOptionSorter
# (null))`.  `ParserProperties` is args4j's
# config-builder pattern: METHOD-CHAINED setters
# `withShowDefaults`, `withUsageWidth`,
# `withOptionSorter`, `withUsageHeader`, etc.
# Distinct from R322 JCommander (no equivalent
# config builder — properties set via the
# `JCommander` instance), R276 picocli (`Command
# Line(cmd).setUsageHelpAutoWidth(true)` etc.).
# args4j's approach: SEPARATE `ParserProperties`
# CONFIG BUILDER object — corpus's **first
# documented ParserProperties-builder-as-config
# CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: amidst uses **args4j
# `@Option(name = "-seed", handler = SeedHandler.
# class, metaVar = "<string>")` with custom
# OptionHandler subclass** at CommandLineParameters.
# java:82-90 + 124-138 — declares a CUSTOM TYPE
# CONVERTER via `handler = SeedHandler.class`.
# The `SeedHandler` is a STATIC NESTED CLASS
# extending `OptionHandler<WorldSeed>` with
# constructor `(CmdLineParser, OptionDef,
# Setter<WorldSeed>)`, overriding
# `parseArguments(Parameters params)` to consume
# argv and call `setter.addValue(parsedValue)`,
# and `getDefaultMetaVariable()` for the help
# placeholder.  This is the args4j SPI for
# integrating domain types into the CLI parser.
# Distinct from R314 Mercury `option_data`
# typed-union default, R311 Guile `(value #t)`
# arg-shape.  Corpus's **first documented
# OptionHandler-SPI-as-custom-type CLI pattern**.
